<TEXT>
after months of 
firefighting with no end in sight officials said tuesday there was 
only one fire burning in and around yellowstone national park and 
it could be contained in three days 
as of tuesday the 387400acre clovermist fire was 90 percent 
contained and the 845 firefighters left on the blaze expected to 
have it contained on friday according to park spokeswoman sandi 
robinson 
the fire which also covers parts of the shoshone national 
forest and into montana has been burning since july 9 one of 
several that have involved an area covering 16 million acres in 
and around the park 
at one time the clovermist blaze threw up 100foot walls of 
flame that dwarfed firefighters trying to get containment lines 
around its perimeter 
as the summer waned however activity has slowed so much fire 
crews have gotten down to cold trailing in which they feel the 
ground with their bare hands in search of hot spots that have yet 
even to produce smoke 
progress also is being made on the 400100acre north fork and 
the 107500acre wolf lake fires in yellowstone and fire crews 
continue to head out of the countrys oldest national park 
however it is too soon to predict when nature will be allowed 
to take over the job of handling the fires robinson said 
we continue to demobilize but as far as when the last 
firefighter will leave the park we just dont know that yet she 
said 
</TEXT>
