<TEXT>
a canadian who lived for years 
in hungary has pleaded innocent in court to four counts of spying 
on american military installations for the soviet union 
stephen joseph ratkai 25 shouted out a firm not guilty 
after each of the four charges was read monday in newfoundland 
supreme court his first court appearance since a preliminary 
inquiry ended early last month 
ratkai is charged with three counts of espionage and one count 
of attempted espionage under the official secrets act 
he is accused of giving the soviet union classified military 
documents about a us submarine tracking base at argentia on 
newfoundlands southern shore 
the information is alleged to be harmful to the security of 
canada and the united states 
chief justice alex hickman set aside a month for ratkais trial 
to begin feb 6 before a judge and jury of the provincial supreme 
court 
ratkai was arrested in june at a local hotel after a lengthy 
investigation by canadian and american officials headed by the 
canadian security intelligence service 
ratkai is the son of a canadian mother and hungarian father who 
emigrated after 1956 when soviet troops entered hungary and quelled 
an anticommunist uprising 
he moved back to hungary with his grandmother at the age of four 
or five 
ratkai later returned to canada and worked as a shortorder cook 
</TEXT>
