most surveyed prices stayed the same or declined 
the bad news is that 29 percent rose and typically these 
increases were quite large he said 
in the survey 14 consumer federation member groups monitored 
prices at major supermarket chains in 16 areas of the country the 
organizations said that comparisons of two sets of prices revealed 
more beef prices rose than fell sirloin prices rose at 35 
percent of the markets and declined at 25 percent of them the 
median increase was 141 cents a pound and the median decrease 90 
cents economists say beef prices should have been falling because 
skyrocketing feed prices accelerated the slaughter 
milk and butter prices were raised more often than lowered in 
the period but the increases were in the range of 3 percent to 5 
percent eighty percent of the stores in the sample did not 
change their price of ice cream 
prices of some wheat products went up faster than expected as 
did those for fresh fruits and vegetables but median price 
decreases for corn and broccoli were typically larger than 
increases even though more stores hiked them than reduced them 
