netherlands antilles five known tax havens where laws protect 
against disclosure bank account information 
the banks are not targets of the investigation but the subpoena 
noted that bank of america paid a 475 million fine in 1986 for 
failing to report 17000 cash deposits and nonelectronic transfers 
in excess of 10000 as required by law there is no law covering 
wire transfers 
irs officials with the san francisco district office which is 
conducting the california portion of the investigation said 
numerous criminal and civil investigations are under way as a 
result of the records obtained from the banks over the past several 
months 
they refused to identify the targets of the investigations or 
name other banks involved in the subpoenas other irs offices are 
conducting similar inquiries they said but declined to name them 
the wiretransfer records enable the irs to construct a pattern 
of transactions by those seeking to get around the us law that 
requires banks to notify the government of transactions of 10000 
or more in cash said alexander d seddio irs criminal 
investigations agent 
to evade the law they make a series of smaller deposits 
consolidate the money in one account and wire it to an offshore 
bank seddio explained any amount of cash can be deposited in an 
offshore bank and wired to a us bank evading the 10000 us 
reporting requirement and making the money appear to be legitimate 
bank of america officials declined to comment on the subpoena or 
the volume of records requested as did wells fargo which recently 
acquired barclays of california bank another reported target of 
the subpoenas 
bank of america is considered particularly vulnerable to money 
laundering because the large number of its branches offers 
anonymity to launderers said the subpoena issued this summer by 
the us attorneys office in san francisco 
