the korean peninsula was divided into communist north korea and 
prowestern south korea in 1945 at the end of world war ii the 
two sides fought a war in the 1950s and the united states still 
maintains 42000 troops in the south parliamentary officials of 
the two koreas are to resume unification talks oct 13 at the truce 
village of panmunjom near the border the last round of talks in 
august ended without any progress 
in early september kim said he would not meet roh unless the 
south accepts north koreas unification formula which calls for 
the two korean states to keep their different political and social 
systems while operating as one nation under a confederation the 
north korean leader also demanded that the two countries 
legislatures issue a joint nonaggression agreement 
seoul officials rejected the demands as a ploy to weaken south 
korea and eventually unify the peninsula under communist rule 
roh said his country would soon propose a new unification 
formula which would be practicable and acceptable to both 
sides but he gave no details 
roh also said south korea which has recently exchanged trade 
offices with hungary and yugoslavia would continue trying to 
improve relations with the soviet union and other communist 
countries 
