<TEXT>
radioactive fallout that drifted over 
isle royale decades ago is helping researchers learn more about the 
moose and wolves that inhabit the island in lake superior 
atmospheric tests of nuclear weapons before 1963 in the western 
united states and the soviet union left traces of radioactive 
carbon 14 in vegetation on the island 
moose that consumed that vegetation began bearing traces of 
carbon 14 in their bones and teeth giving scientists a way to 
track the migration of herds said rolf peterson leader of a 
michigan technological university research team 
weve collected the bones from almost 1900 moose that have 
died from various causes on isle royale over the past 30 years 
peterson said 
we want to measure the amount of carbon 14 in their teeth and 
use it as a marker to determine each individuals year of birth and 
the herds survival patterns and population age structure 
the study might help researchers better understand the role of 
michigans estimated 1600 moose in a food chain that includes 
timber wolves peterson said 
we believe the nutritional state of moose in winter largely 
determines their lifelong ability to survive he said that in 
turn determines the amount of food available for wolves and 
ultimately wolf density 
we hope the information were gathering now will not only tell 
us more about the moose herd but when combined with existing data 
will also help us explain longterm fluctuations in the wolf 
population on isle royale 
peterson said the atmospheric bomb tests banned since 1963 
doubled the amount of carbon 14 in the atmosphere todays level is 
still about 20 percent higher than before the tests began he said 
its a reminder of how longlasting this stuff actually is 
he said weve got it in our teeth too 
peterson said the studies might also determine if the 1986 
reactor accident at the soviet unions chernobyl nuclear power 
plant affected michigans moose 
peterson who has studied moose and wolf populations for 18 
years said the threeyear study is being financed by a 150000 
grant from the national science foundation 
</TEXT>
