focus on allegheny county pa the pittsburgh area in their 
efforts for a voluntary doortodoor aids survey that could lead to 
a more comprehensive national survey an official said today 
public health service jim brown said the centers for disease 
control a part of phs turned their attention to pittsburgh after 
district of columbia health officials and other community leaders 
complained that the sampling planned for the capital city appeared 
to be unfairly targeted at black neighborhoods 
the plan is for federal and local health officials to approach 
residents to ask for a blood sample to test for aids in an effort 
to get a more scientific handle on how much the virus has spread 
the idea is to do the sampling much the way polls are conducted 
so a representative portion of the population is tested but 
instead of being asked questions the people selected for the 
survey will be asked to let their blood be tested for aids 
the blood samples would not be identified by name 
top federal health officials have been skeptical that enough 
people would submit to the voluntary testing to enable them to get 
a representative sampling on a national basis 
the pittsburgh study is designed not so much to learn the extent 
of aids infection in that area as to determine whether sampling 
techniques can be developed that would make a national survey 
worthwhile 
