the study also divided american women into four groups with 
significantly different attitudes toward food shopping and cooking 
traditional homemakers who make up 31 percent of all women 
believe its the husbands job to support the family 
displaced homemakers 26 percent of all women have 
unfulfilling jobs out of financial necessity or because of divorce 
or separation but would rather be a fulltime homemaker 
committed careerists 33 percent who see marriage and 
childrearing as an interruption of their careers 
free spirits 11 percent who dont fit any of the other 
categories most reside in large urban areas are relatively 
young employed and divorced or separated many are minorities 
they have the shopping habits of traditional homemakers but cook 
like committed careerists 
mark clements research inc and national family opinion inc 
conducted the study for conde nast publications it mailed 2500 
questionnaires on dec 4 and got back 1825 by jan 12 from women 
18 to 65 years old the sampling error was plus or minus 24 
percent 
</TEXT>
