<TEXT>
political killings torture and detention without 
trial are widespread in asia amid civil and ethnic conflicts in 
large parts of the continent amnesty international said wednesday 
in its annual report on a global survey the organization cited 
24 asian countries for alleged human rights violations in 1987 
it said soviet and afghan troops often in reprisal attacks 
against anticommunist rebels killed dozens of unarmed civilians 
in afghanistan unlawful killings by government forces also were 
reported in the philippines indonesia sri lanka and india 
the report from the londonbased international human rights 
group included these allegations 
in the philippines security forces or governmentbacked 
vigilante groups killed more than 100 leftwing political 
activists members of labor unions and peasant organizations 
several thousand political detainees were held in india without 
charge or trial under antiterrorist laws and a government inquiry 
into the massacre of scores of unarmed moslems produced no results 
there were continued killings in sri lanka of tamil civilians 
often in reprisal for attacks by militant tamil groups fighting for 
a separate state 
between 1983 and the end of 1987 more than 680 tamils 
disappeared in sri lanka and it is believed many were shot or 
tortured to death by security forces most tamils are hindus and 
claim discrimination by sri lankas buddhist sinhalese majority 
amnesty international said governments used a variety of methods 
to suppress criticism 
it said singapore and malaysia imposed press laws allowing the 
government absolute authority to restrict any publication deemed to 
have engaged in domestic politics or to have alarmed public 
opinion 
in south korea it is against the law to give information to 
foreigners that officials judge could insult or slander the 
state the report said 
it also said a majority of asian countries carried out 
courtimposed executions amnesty international opposes the death 
sentence as inhumane punishment 
the report said that in china more than 200 convicted criminals 
were put to death for offenses ranging from murder and rape to drug 
smuggling theft and showing pornographic movies but that 
figure represents only a fraction of the total number of death 
sentences and executions it said 
at least 70 people were sentenced to death in pakistan but the 
real total may have been considerably higher the report said 
</TEXT>
