<TEXT>
on a recent weekday the rev 
alphonse stephenson is chainsmoking and still managing to talk at 
a rapidfire pace filling the air with cigarette smoke and waving 
arms 
even in church on sunday parishioners accustomed to a quiet 
mass are either delighted or somewhat taken aback when the 
38yearold priest bounces down the aisles filling his sermons 
with humorous stories and priesttoparishioner banter 
stephenson throws himself into the priesthood with a joyful 
abandon but its not his only devotion 
im a professional musician called to be a priest he said 
ive seen too many priests who are burned out because they look 
at the priesthood as a profession 
from 1980 to 1986 stephenson took a fulltime leave of absence 
from the ministry to serve as conductor for a chorus line both 
on the national tour and on broadway 
after his performances he relaxed at his grandparents home in 
point pleasant beach a cottage where a black concert piano 
dominates the living room and a talkative gray parrot rules the 
dining room 
he became involved in religious life again by making friends 
with priests at the local church st peter by the sea soon he 
found himself helping the shortstaffed parish by celebrating 
sunday mass 
the return to a religious atmosphere came at the same time that 
stephenson felt a need to do different kinds of music something 
beyond a chorus line 
i wanted to do a concert he said 
he called upon a local musicians union and found 42 very 
interested colleagues in april 1986 they gave their first concert 
at st peter by the sea it was an instant success stephenson 
said inspiring people who were surprised to hear beethoven and 
other classical composers in a church setting 
a church is where the origin of majestry begins he said 
its a very different religious experience 
and after paying the musicians the church was able to realize 
a nice profit stephenson said 
soon afterward the musical priest met roger bernier a local 
financial consultant who now serves as the orchestras business 
manager 
together we began thinking if the orchestra makes such a 
profit for one pastor why cant it have the same effect for other 
parishes stephenson said 
in its first year as a formal group the orchestra of st peter 
by the sea raised more than 250000 for charitable organizations 
in the new jersey area bernier said 
organizations needing money hold raffles bingo pot luck 
suppers a typical 1950s dance to raise funds but then they start 
to run out of ideas stephenson said 
at first many are skeptical of a classical concert in a church 
setting because they expect a religious flavor he said the 
concerts do have a religious bent but i talk to the audience 
describe the music and how the musicians are feeling and the 
emotions of the composer at the time he wrote the piece 
many symphony orchestras have lost audiences because they fail 
to teach the finer points bernier said 
the orchestra of st peter by the sea is looking to expand its 
audience bernier said perhaps by performing at colleges and in 
other states stephenson would also like to perform in large 
churches he fondly recalls a concert at st pauls church in new 
york city that was absolutely majestic 
stephensons next project is to create a sacred music program 
for large acoustically perfect beautiful cathedrals that have 
never heard this music in years 
the music would be along the scope of a production such as the 
wellknown handels messiah he said but would concentrate on 
longlost religious works that modern orchestras would probably 
never consider 
ideally the priest hopes to find benefactors who would 
financially support such a venture to open it to the public for 
free 
id be looking for older people who feel the church needs this 
again people concerned about the arts who see that the church was 
always a preserver and promoter of the arts he said 
another challenge will be to persuade a prospective audience to 
listen to a sacred music performance stephenson said 
people will not leave the church and say oh ive been 
converted he said im suggesting that it could be used as a 
motivator of faith whatever your faith may be 
stephenson maintains that his concerts could move even a 
17yearold fan of new wave rock music 
parents make a big mistake in the united states when they say 
things like oh thats their music he said twisted sister 
might be jolly to teenagers now but i wonder when they turn 80 if 
theyll get the same enjoyment out of it and if it will refresh 
their soul 
</TEXT>
