a federal judge has approved a reorganization plan 
for placid oil co owned by the trust estates of the hunt brothers 
of dallas 
the move approved friday by us bankruptcy judge harold 
abramson clears the way for the settlement of a twoyear dispute 
between the hunts and their lenders over 15 billion in bank loans 
william herbert hunt nelson bunker hunt and lamar hunt and 17 
of their creditor banks proposed the plan which had been 
previously announced 
it calls for 663 million in payments and a sevenyear note for 
140 million which will be secured by profits from producing 
properties 
the hunts have paid 2235 million and will raise another 200 
million through the sale of their interest in the downtown dallas 
office building thanksgiving tower and placids stake in the black 
lake natural gas field in louisiana a 10year loan with dutch 
banks and secured by the hunts north sea oil and gas operations 
will raise another 240 million 
the transactions are expected to close in several weeks 
completing the settlement and releasing placid from chapter 11 
bankruptcy a hunt spokesman said 
the other half of the hunts 15 billion in bank debts was 
settled last month when a separate reorganization plan was 
approved for the three hunt trusts the former sole owners of 
penrod drilling co 
under that 750 million settlement the hunt trusts were 
discharged from chaper 11 bankruptcy 
bunker hunt and herbert hunt filed personal bankruptcy petitions 
last month after losing a 134 million federal court judgment in 
connection with silver transactions they made in the late 1970s 
</TEXT>
