<TEXT>
the day after democratic presidential 
candidate michael dukakis unveiled an innovative student loan 
program harvard economist lawrence h summers was quoted in 
newspapers around the country explaining how it would work 
it wasnt a coincidence summers one of the nations top young 
economists has emerged as a point man in a coterie of outside 
advisers to the massachusetts governor in his bid for the white 
house 
summers is there when the candidate needs an economic position 
paper or a quick assessment of what the latest unemployment figures 
mean 
and as the candidates staff enters the final weeks of the 
campaign against vice president george bush summers is one of a 
handful of policy experts eggheads called upon daily to 
help shape positions and strategy 
when we hit an issue we think who are the best people we can 
turn to said robert j shapiro deputy issues director for 
economics on the dukakis campaign there are a couple of people 
who play a special role in that they are consulted on a wide range 
of issues certainly larry is one of them 
summers is a macroeconomic specialist who shares dukakis belief 
that government should play a larger role in encouraging 
investment promoting business and aiding the middle class what 
he calls a helping hands policy to replace the invisible 
hand of the reagan administration 
like other liberal economists summers contends that the 
enormous national debt amassed in the last eight years makes the 
economic prosperity so touted by republicans nothing more than a 
house of cards 
theres a sense of unease summers said in a recent 
interview in his harvard university office that sense i think is 
a more important thing than the feeling of prosperity people have 
at the moment theyre aware of the fragility of that prosperity 
and the fact that it is borrowed 
according to summers foreign acquisitions of us companies 
will triple this year over last median family income is around 
1969 levels government spending on the nations infrastructure is 
onefifth of 1960s levels support for university research has 
dropped 95 percent since 1980 38 million americans are without 
health insurance homelessness has tripled under president reagan 
as a nation we havent looked to the future and were in 
danger of not being ready when the future comes he said 
as a surrogate spokesman for the campaign summers has become 
politically more astute in recent months stepping up attacks on 
bush and toning down some earlier more candid pronouncements on 
economic issues where he once said reducing the deficit requires 
higher taxes now he says of the tword i think it would depend 
on the political and economic situation following the election 
just 33 years old summers credentials are daunting which 
shouldnt be a surprise considering his economics lineage 
summers parents anita and robert both are professors at the 
university of pennsylvania and two uncles paul samuelson at the 
massachusetts institute of technology and kenneth arrow at stanford 
university have won nobel prizes 
summers graduated from mit at age 20 and earned his doctorate 
from harvard in 1982 a year before joining the faculty at age 28 
last year he became the first social scientist to receive an annual 
500000 national science foundation award 
before coming to harvard summers spent 10 months on the staff 
of the president reagans council of economic advisers an 
experience he said left him disillusioned 
there was less emphasis on helping everyone in the country 
rather than meeting the needs of the privileged few he said of 
the republican assignment 
like other members of dukakis kitchen cabinet summers became 
involved in the campaign through harvard connections he had 
tutored jack corrigan the campaigns operations director who last 
year recommended tapping summers 
with just three economists and about 30 recent college 
graduates the campaigns economics staff relies on outside 
advisers in business government and the private sector on beacon 
hill capitol hill and wall street 
in addition to summers key figures include robert rubin vice 
chairman of the investment firm goldman sachs co rudy oswald 
head of economic research for the aflcio robert reich the 
iconoclastic professor at harvards kennedy school of government 
and dan tarullo a staffer on the senate labor committee 
the point of talking to larry and lots of other people is to 
be sure we get it right to be sure that weve seen all the aspects 
of an issue and that we understand it correctly shapiro said 
were looking for more than a sound bite on the news were 
thinking about how best to govern this country and thats serious 
business so we use serious people 
summers helped develop the financing features and then publicly 
explained the college loan plan proposed by dukakis last month 
designed to aid middleincome families the program allows students 
to repay loans by withholding a small fixed percentage of income 
over a lifetime 
larry was one of the people involved in pulling together the 
details said dukakis issues director christopher b edley jr a 
kennedy school graduate and harvard law professor he took a lead 
in getting in touch with people other economists and in thinking 
through the financing mechanisms 
edley said summers unlike other eggheads has an ability to 
push a button and stop being an academic professor 
hes been remarkably helpful at working on speech lines or 
thinking about events to communicate the message he said hes 
been surprisingly good in ways one might not think an academic 
would be 
moreover summers has been willing to take on assigned tasks 
answer calls at all hours and provide viewpoints that may differ 
from his own 
its easy enough to find somebody who has a lot of stature and 
smarts wholl be happy to spend a day briefing the governor on how 
to be leader of the free world edley said its harder to find 
someone who is willing to get their hands dirty 
</TEXT>
