joe m henson is stepping down as president 
and chief executive officer of prime computer inc and will be 
succeeded after a transition period by former general electric co 
executive anthony craig prime said tuesday 
henson 55 has been chief executive of the natickbased 
computer maker since november 1981 the company did not give any 
reason for his departure but said he notified the board last year 
that he intended to leave henson said he has no longterm plans 
other than to attend to personal business and take a lengthy 
vacation 
craig 43 is stepping in immediately as chief operating 
officer executive vice president and a member of the board after 
a transition of a few months he will assume hensons posts 
according to company spokesman richard eckel 
craig has been president of ges information services division 
since september 1986 he joined that division in 1983 as vice 
president of international sales after 17 years as a marketing and 
product management executive for international business machines 
inc 
prime reported earnings of 648 million on revenues of 961 
million in 1987 the company is projecting revenues of about 16 
billion this year with a lage part of the increase resulting from 
its 435 million purchase of computervision inc in february 
the computervision takeover made prime second only to ibm in the 
market for computeraided design and manufacturing systems in may 
prime announced about 700 layoffs because of job redundancies 
associated with the takeover 
in addition prime announced in july that it was withdrawing 
from the minisupercomputer market and taking a 5 million charge 
against earnings 
